          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Which feature is present in the mid-thoracic (T6) cross-section of the spinal cord but absent in the mid-cervical (C6) cross-section?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>A large anterior horn serving numerous limb muscles</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The anterior horn is actually larger at C6, not T6. The cervical enlargement supplies the upper limb muscles via the brachial plexus, requiring more motor neurons than the thoracic level which serves only trunk muscles.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>A lateral horn containing sympathetic preganglionic neurons</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The lateral horn is present only between T1 and L2, where it houses sympathetic preganglionic neurons. At C6, which is above T1, there is no lateral horn — this is a reliable way to distinguish cervical from thoracic cross-sections.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Extensive white matter surrounding the grey matter</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>White matter is actually more extensive at C6 than at T6. Higher cord levels accumulate more ascending and descending fibres from all the segments below them.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>A posterior horn receiving incoming sensory information</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The posterior horn is present at every spinal cord level, including both C6 and T6. It receives incoming sensory information throughout the cord and is not a distinguishing feature between these two cross-sections.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The lateral horn is the key distinguishing feature. It is present only between T1 and L2 for sympathetic outflow, making it visible at T6 but absent at C6."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. The lateral horn, containing sympathetic preganglionic neurons, is the hallmark of thoracic and upper lumbar cross-sections (T1–L2)."
                }
              ],
