            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Which spinal cord condition produces both upper and lower motor neuron signs while leaving sensation completely intact?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Brown-Séquard syndrome</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Brown-Séquard syndrome is a hemisection that produces ipsilateral motor loss AND contralateral pain and temperature loss. Sensation is clearly affected — the crossed sensory deficit defines this syndrome.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. ALS (motor neuron disease) damages both the corticospinal tract (upper motor neurons) and the anterior horn cells (lower motor neurons). Because only motor pathways are involved, sensation remains completely intact — a key diagnostic feature.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Syringomyelia</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Syringomyelia damages the anterior white commissure first, causing a cape-like loss of pain and temperature across the shoulders and arms. Sensation is prominently affected, not spared.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Transverse myelitis</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Transverse myelitis inflames the entire cord cross-section, causing complete sensory loss below the lesion along with bilateral motor paralysis and autonomic dysfunction.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (motor neuron disease) is the answer. It uniquely damages both the corticospinal tract and anterior horn cells, producing combined UMN and LMN signs, while all sensory pathways remain completely unaffected."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. ALS is unique among cord syndromes because it affects only motor neurons at two levels — corticospinal tract (UMN) and anterior horn cells (LMN) — while sensory pathways remain intact."
                }
              ],
